{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_indio_ver01/data/sn85066387/0017504789A/1908061801/0353.xml":{"full_text":"SECOND SECTION\nVOLUME CIV.\u2014 NO. 18;\nFirst Step Is Taken by City for Securing Hetch Hetchy Water Supply\nCALLS BARTNETT\nDIRTY DOG AND\nCRINGING CUR\nJ. Dalzell Brown Gives Vent\nto Passionate Hatred of\nFormer Partner\nBlames Associate for Aiding in\nHis Indictment for Em\nbezzlement\nAttorney Baits Convicted Banker\nInto Expression of Bitter\nFeeling\n\"I think the man that sits behind\nyou is a dirty dog, and, if you want to\nknow, a cringing cur!\"\nIn these words, bitter with a pas\nsionate hatred, J. Dalzell Brown, the\nconvict, yesterday denounced his for\nmer colleague, Walter J. Bartnett,\nwho is on trial for embezzlement be\nfore Judge Conley of Madera, sitting\nin Judge Cook's department of the su\nperior court.\nThe outburst of feeling came after\ndays of constant meeting in the court\nroom, during which Bartnett r and\nBrown have ignored each other's very\nexistence. Never before, since the trial\nbegan, have their eyes met, and never\nhave they exchanged a single word.\nIt was Attorney Geary of Bartnetfs\nlegal staff who, by his Questions to the\nwitness, opened the way for the ex\ncoriation, and once Brown was forced\nto. speak he spoke plainly. His face\n\\u25a0was ashen as he turned his eyes slawly\nfrom Geary to fix them full on Bart\nnett, who eat directly behind his at\ntorn ey, an<J when he spoke it was with\ns. tenseness of feeling: that caused a\nsudden hush to fall on the courtroom.\nBAIITXETrS FLVGERS TWITCH :'i\u00a3\nBartnett paled slightly as Brown,\nspeaking to Geary, but looking directly\nat him, gave utterance to his inmost\nfeelings, and his fingers twitched nerv\nously for an instant and then clenched\nthemselves against his palms. But\nBartnett did not answer. A moment\nafter Brown had spoken the noon re\ncess of court was ordered and, in the\nconfusion of adjournment, Bartnett re\ngained his composure and turned coldly\naway as Brown passed him on the way\nout of the room.\nGeary, who was conducting the cross\nexamination of the witness, had been\nfiaying Brown mercilessly, forcing him\nto tell every detail of his shame, of his\nadmission of guilt and his sentence to\nthe penitentiary, but withal masking\nt lie inquiry with a veneer of politeness\nthat gave Brown no opportunity to an\nswer back. And so if was that Brown,\nwrithing under the torture, failed to\nhold himself in check when Bartnetfs\nname was mentioned. Geary had se\ncured from Brown a statement that the\nlatter believed his indictment was\nfounded on information furnished by\nAllan Griffiths, Bartnetfs brother in\nJaw, to the attorney general.\n\"But for that information, that was\nfurnished by Allan Griffiths, you would\nrot now be a convict?\" questioned\nI \"Of course you are in love with Allan\nriffiths?\" taunted Geary.\n\"Yes, ar.4 with his brother in law.\"\nROWN BLA3IES BOTH\n\"And you blame them both for your\nresent position?\"\n\"I do.\"\n\"And your feeling: is very bitter to\nard both Bartnett and his brother in\nw because you think the information\nhich they furnished, or whicli you say\nley furnished, was the cause of your\nmvictlon?\"\nThe color ebbed suddenly from\nrown's face and he turned in his chair\nlook directly over Geary's head at\nartnett. \"When he spoke every word\nas enunciated sharply and distinctly.\n\"I think the man that sits behind you\na. dirty dog, and if you want to\nlow a cringing cur.\"\nFor an instant there was no sound In\nthe courtroom and then Geary pro\npounded another question his voice\nsoft and persuasive.\n\"Do you want to say anything more?\"\nhe asked. \"Go on.\"\n\"That's enough for the present,\" re\nrponded Brown in trembling tones.\nBrown's cross examination was con\ncluded yesterday afternoon and. there\nIs every Indication that the case will be\nready for the jury by tomorrow after\nnoon. Prosecutor Cook stated to the\n\\u25a0 court that he expected to close in a\nshort time this morning and the de\nfense announced that the taking of its\ntestimony would not extend over a\ncouple of hours. This would leave Fri\nday for the closing arguments and in\nstructions, and unless unexpected In\nterruptions develop the case Bhould be\ngiven to the jury, before adjournment\n5* taken Friday afternoon.\nKXEW RECEIPT'S FALSITY\nBrown testified yesterday that when\nhe signed the receipt given by the bank\n-for tb\u00ab Colton securities he knew that\nno Western Pacific bonds were con\ntained in the package and that the re\nceipt was false, but that he relied upon\nBartnetfs statement that the course\nwould be all right.\n\"I elgned it because I trusted in a\n.friend,\" he said.\nBrown admitted that the Colton se\nctlritles were not the only ones'embez\nzled by the bank officials. He said that\nthree Western Pacific bonds belonging\nto Mrs. Helen Lake Hunter were sold\nand that three bonds of the Pacific\n\u2022window glass company were substi\n\"tuted for them, that five Western Pa\nciflc bonds belonging to I Eva Murray\nw\u00abre sold and replaced by bonds of the\nCarnegie brick and; pottery company\nTaft on Reasonable Platform Will Insure\nEarly Return of Prosperity\nMany People Alarmed by Political Conditions\nIn response to The Call's request; Paul Morton, president\nof the Equitable life, sends from Nev> York the following con-,\nservative but optimistic forecast of prosperity v\nI HESITATE to make pre\ndictions 1 because so many\nunforeseen things may\narise to change conditions, but\nit seems to me that the fact\nthat there will be a presiden\ntial election this fair is quite\ncertain to deter people from\nentering into new enterprises.\nThis will make money much\neasier than it has been for\nseveral years past, and I doubt\nif we will see any very high\nrates the coming autumn. In\nmy opinion money is quite\nlikely^ to accumulate at -the\n\u2022\\u25a0'money centers, and it will hot-\nv v surprise me 'to see bank de\nposits pass all previous* records...\nThe chief obstacle in the* way of immediate return of pros\nperity is politics. Mariy^people, at home and abroad; are\nalarmed about the future political conditions mii America. If,\nit were definitely settled that .Mr. Taft is to.be our next presi\ndent, on a reasonable platform, and that we were to have .good\"\ncrops and fair prices for our products, I believe that the return\nof prosperity would be early.\nWe live in a great country. Its resources. are vast; its people\nare industrious. The letting up in our. business activity wijl\nnot last long, and we are just as certain of making great\nstrides, commercially and financially, from, trite time on as* we\nalways have been sure of doing so. The man who bets on the\ncountry and its;- future -greatness is- one \"who will ulti\nmately win. .\\u25a0_ \\u25a0:-.\\u25a0\\u25a0\\u25a0'\\u25a0-. r': \\u25a0-' -.'~\\r \\u25a0 ,v' Y.- '\\u25a0 \"'\\u25a0 -.\\u25a0\\u25a0*!;\u2022\"\nPAUL MORTON\nJune 2, 1908.\nCommontawWifeMs\n$2,ooo,oooEstate\nAged Spanish Woman Seeks to\nRecover Part of Money\nShe Helped to Earn\nSPECIAL, .DISPATCH TO THE CAIX\nSAXTA BARBARA, June 17.\u2014 Dominga\nSchiappipietra, 80 years old, common\nlaw wife of Federlco Schiappipietra,\nwho died several years i ago, has\nbrought suit in the superior court here\nfor an accounting from the executors\nof the estate of Leopoldo Schiappi\npietra, filing a claim to a share in her\nhusband's $2,000,000 estate In this\ncounty and Ventura.\nForty years ago Schiappipietra\nstarted a little grocery here and\nfrom the profits he bought .an 8,000\nacre ranch In Ventura. His common\nlaw wife, a Spanish woman, bore him\nfive children during his life at the\nranch.\nAfter his death his will made no\nmention of the faithful woman who\nhelped him thrive and no mention was\nmade of the children. The estate was\nleft to the man's brother, Antonio, who\ncame to America penniless. The'chil\ndren in ISSB sued- to recover their\nfather's estate. They were persuaded\nto settle. Antonio died in Ventura in\n1895,' leaving: the estate to a third\nbrother, Leopoldo. When Leopoldo died\nrecently in Italy he left the property\nto his relatives in southern' California.\nNow the widow of the man who made\nthe Schiappipietra fortune possible\nhas brought suit for $1,000,000.\nand'the Pacific window glass company,\nand that three Western Pacific bonds\nbelonging to Andrew Hall were -dis\nposed of in the same way. The pro\nceeds of the sales were used to assist\nthe bank and the less valuable bonds\nof the subsidiary companies substituted\nfor the railroad bonds which were\nstolen.\nBank Commissioner Lynch followed\nBrown on the stand and corroborated\nthe testimony given by J. Cal Ewing\nto the effect that Brown and Bartnett\nhad told the bank commissioners after,\nthe bank failure that the missing Col\nton securities had been burned or were\nin a safe deposit box in New York.\nJURYMAN IS INJURED\nJ. H.Flynn Struck by Plank\nWhich Falls From Building\nJ H. Fiynn; a member of the Jury In\nJudge Conley's court -which is trying\nWalter J. Bartnett on. a charge of em\nbezzlement 1 of securities from the Cali^\nfornia safe- deposit anditrust company,\nwas slightly hurt and narrowly escaped\nfatal injury while' on his way\" to the\ncourt yesterday: after the noon, recess.\nThe i jury, -in \\charge. .of. :two deputy\nsheriff\u00df,.-was marching -to the court\nfrom*the St. \"^.Francis; hotel,*- where the\nmembers are, locked up; .wheni, as they\npassed a building; lnUhe course of'con\n\u00abstructi6h\"\"*in Geary..; streets between\nL\u00abavenworth and Hyde sUeets, a heavy\nplank was /dropped ..from a fourth story\n\\u25a0elevation. 1 The timber -struck Flynn -on\nthe head, but; glanced \"off,'; causing;: only\na bad; scalp wound: Flynn wa*s: almost\nunconscious f or> a f e w mornents,';.but\nwas carried into '\\u25a0 a drug 1 \\u25a0. store and i rei\nvived. He was able; after; a short' rest,'\nto -.proceed \\u25a0' to the Y courtroom and-; sit\nthrough the afternoon\" session of the\nPaul Morton\nKat^arls\u00df|ocked?by\nWedding Plans-\nDrs. Blue and Rucker 'Too Busy\nfor Event to Meet Sanitary\nCommission\nRats may have their good points\nmay even be interesting; as a study\nbut after all how could a small, rodent\never be expected to hold his own\nagainst a large military wedding? Rats\nwe have always with .us\u2014 weddings\nonly now and then. Rats are abso\nlutely unappreciatlve of pearl gloves\nand silk hats and boutonnleres; clothes\nare nothing to them. And weddings,\nand the; flurry of dressing for wed\ndings, are, dear to the human heart\ndear to -the masculine as well as \"the\nfeminine heart, it would seem.\nWhich is the reason that neither Dr\nRupert Blue nor Dr. W.C. Rucker ap\npeared at the meeting of the. women's\nauxiliary of the sanitary commission\nyesterday morning. I\nPREPARE FOR WEDDIXG\n\"Dr. Rucker says that he is getting\nDr. Blue ready, for a wedding that they,\nare going\" to attend at noon,\" said\nMadame Emilia Tojetti, smilingly, as\nshe returned from the telephone yes\nterday, \"and so we must get along by\nourselves.\"\nThis message was received. by sym\npathetic hearers who have struggled\nwith wedding garments, themselves and\nso were* able to forgive theabsent offi\ncers. The regular business of the meet-\nIng went on, one\"of the- most impor\ntant motions that was made being one\nIn favor of a six weeks' adjournment,\nwhich was carried unanimously.; The\nnext meeting, of the there\nfore, wiH take \\u25a0'/\"place? on. the -last\nWednesday in August; when the mem\nbers, many of whom go to .the country\nthis week, will return refreshed and\n\\u25a0rested for the winter's work.\nA lecture, or a series of lectures with\nstereopticon views, will. open the next\nseason's work. Dr. Converse of the\nsecond federal district addressed the\nmembers and guests, speaking at, length\nof the improved .condition in the city\nsince the sanitation', movement was\ncommenced.. i\nMrs. J. C. Levy^ who. Is 'in charge! of\none of the -largest districts, reported\nupon investigations; recently made *&s\nto the method, employed by, wholesale\ndealers in bringing vegetables into the\ncity. Mrs. Levy explained ithat;. al\nthough there was an ordinance,enforc\ning: the washing of. manure carts be\nfore they are used for \"vegetables,\"\nthe law worked a hardship* upon the\nowners of the carts, who complained\nthat it was impossible ;to wash the\nwagons between\"\" the hours that they\nwere obliged to use^ them- for one, thing\nor another. }'=':,':j';--\\ .Ki r-^r\nVEGETABLES IX MAAURE CARTS \\u25a0\\u25a0\\u25a0'.\nSeveral of* the members \u2022present\nshocked and surprised to learn ;\"that~ for\nmany v years vegetables V^have J been\nbrought into \\u25a0 the city. In '\"carts L- f or\nmerly.!used for mariure,'and:, they ihave*\nresolved not; to let^the m'atte^restluhtil\nsome}; step\", has. been^taken^towafd^a 1\nbetter state! -of- affairs.^ Several\nwere read yesterday /and' the~t business\n,was .laid upon s theshelf until .the'work\nrecommences after? the;' summer \"vaca-^\ntlons.'; ...-\\u25a0'. \\u25a0\\u25a0;\"!-. _ \\u25a0'.'\\u25a0:\u2022\"..'\\u25a0..\nV; Aboutra score of' Women were pres\nent yesterday,- among them being:\nMrs. /A.^i.W.\" -Scott -~-i? Mrs. 7 Henry il'ayot\nMrs. -Mary Fairbrother< Mrs.\"; George EVanu \\u25a0 ''\\u25a0*\u2022'\nMrs. A. 'E...Gunn: Mrs/vIY ll.. 'Abbott*.*\nMrM Helen Moored i Mme.*' Emilia.' Tojetti\nMrs.*? Theodore J Pllntber Mrs. 1 Mary* Sperrj -7,-\nMrs. ?J. C.-Lery Mrs. T.% Jordan\nMm. \\u25a0 A. \\u25a0'. M.: Simpson \\u25a0 r '\\u25a0*\nSAN FR^TCISCOH THURSD^ JUNE '18,? 1908.\nDREAM SHOWS\nBODY OF BOY\nIN PARK LAKE\nDetective McMahon VVision of\nGrandnephew Made Reality\nby Grappling Hooks\nPolice Find Child Missing Four\nDays Near Raft From\nWhich He Fell\nBelieve You ng Comrade Knew\nof Drowning but Feared\nto Teli Truth\nA dream that came to Detective\nGeorge McMahon foretold the finding\nyesterday of the body of little Cyril\nRobertson of 549 \\u25a0 Frederick street in\nMud lake, Golden Gate park, off the\nsouth drive and near Twenty-fourth\navenue. For -four days the police,\nfriends and A playmates of the lad\nsearched for him in the park, and yes\nterday morning the -work of dragging\nthe park' lakes 'was begun. Death\ncame to the lad, whose disappearance\nhas been a four days' mystery, while\nhe-was-playing on a raft.C\nMcMahon, who r.was a grand uncle, of\nthe lad, dreamed Tuesday night- that\nthe remains would be found *In -Mud\nlake. At first he paid little attention\nto the premonition of the night. But\nearly yesterday morning he went to\nthe out of the way body, of water and\nstationed himself there 'to await\" the\ncoming of. the draggers detailed from\nthe water, front by the harbor commis\nsioners.\nDuring the .forenoon Martin Mc-\nGowen and Hector Brodie, equipped\nwith grappling- hooks, arrived at the\nlake. A raft drifted idly in the, cen\nter of the pond and a pole floated on\nthe smooth surface near at hand. Po\nlice 'Sergeant -Rainsbtiry and .Pollce\nmen:Haley and Harrington, with the\ntwo water front employes,: launched a\nboat and rowed, out to the raft.. De\ntective McMahon watched them from\nthe bank, the vivid picture of his\ndream focused upon, his. mind. _\nSEE.sYbODY IX DREAM\n\"Lastnlght I saw Cyril in a dream.\nI saw him clearly. He was lying. face\nup in the! center, of the pond. There\nwas a smile: on- his lips,\". McMahon\nsaid as; he 'described his dream as the'\nsearchers worked.\nThe boat was i rowed silently to the\nraft. The first drag merely\" disturbed\nthe reeds at the bottom of the: lake.'\nA second cast was made. The grap-'\npllng hooks came up heavy\u2014 heavy\nwith the weight of the dead body of\nlittle Cyril Robertson.\nMcMahon -was among those who\nstood \u2022on .the shore as the body was\nbrought to land.\n\"As I said,\" declares the i detective,\n\"there-is a smile.on his lips.\"\nThe police hold a suspicion -that\n9 -year-old Milton -.Valentine was with\nthe Robertson; lad when the. f latter,\ncame to his death, \"but was so. j stung\nby; the horror- of the tragedy and] made\nso nervous by t the. fact that'he' \\u25a0'\u2022: was\nthe \\u25a0 sole witness S to 'the death that he\ndreaded -to ttelli the truth. -The .Valen\ntine lad spent; Saturday af ternoon with\nCyril 'at! the stadium^ baseball gTOund.\nWhen -he returned^ home \"i he declared\nthat he had become separated; from i his\nplaymate^ In ..the: crowd. -He told \\u25a0\"-his\nstory in a faltering .way,; the police\nsay.\" :J; 3J,--\" \\u25a0\\u25a0\\u25a0:\\u25a0-' \\u25a0' \\u25a0*\\u25a0\\u25a0'\\u25a0 -\u2022'\\u25a0 \\u25a0 '\".'\\u25a0 '\\u25a0' y, \\u25a0\nPARENTS INTERFERE \\u25a0,'-.\nDetective Dow; tried, to Interview 'the\nlad r yesterday,^ but^ his; parents liwould\nnot permit him .tol be freely, queatlonedf\nDow :i stated >that/heT;believedithe\nlads were'.togetheriwheri; Robertson fell\ninto't'the-'lake^arid^- that r the T;iterrible\ncalamity; to*., his playmate (unnerved:; the\nValentine K boy, 'to g. such^i an extent that\nhe 'it eared, he) might 1 be jheld)toi account\nfor ;the,dlsaster.\"ii It\\- Is fconsldered icer\ntain- thatVCyril Jwas floating \\u25a0oii v th'el raft\n.when he\" fell .'in to\" the '.water.- \\u25a0 *\\u25a0 \\u25a0? -Z\"~V\ni^TheS fourth;; day-.of -the.search for\niittl'e'Cyrilj\u00dfobertson^was to \"haye \\u25a0 '.been'\nlmarkediby ii thor.6ush':,w6rk.* TAt.BT At.B o'clock\nyesterday jmorning; 50 'policemen;' lri< two\ndivisions, headed gby^Sergeants Ross\niandg\u00dfainsburytandl augmented ;-by~\" 100\nContinued on Pase 12, Middle Coin mn 2\nCyril; Robertson, whose body was found -in) Mud j lake, on\nJ southern borderj of Golden .Gate park. Diagram^ showing posi-\nI tiens of body, .raft an$ \\u25a0-pole and^ photograph of lake where lad\nmet his death; v' '.*'\\u25a0.-.\n\"Indefatigable\" Biggy\nHas Close Call\nEscapes Being Shot for High'\nway man by. Hair of His M us\niache In Hunting Speeders\nAn indefatigable chief of .police. That\nis the sort J of man'; that William Blggy\nis.; He has thoroughly, convinced* even\nthe most skeptical that he; Is deserving\nof the adjective. In earning the appel\nlation j Chief of Police Blggy came -'as\nnear as anything* to -capturing a .vio\nlator,\" of the '\\u25a0/ automobile speed, ordi\nnance\u2014he would^ have i made the cap\nture: if' he hadn't idodged \"most adroitly.\nAnd'- he came still nearerito \\bein^ mis\ntaken for a highwayman, by J, two of his\nstout- policemen.'! *He\" would; have 'been\nif he hadn't hollered tolbeat the niuffler.\nBlggy, earnest worshiper at the shrine\nof adages,* has a\\worthy mott\u00ab>-^\"Take\ncare of the misdemeanprs 'and' the fel\nonies; .will \\u25a0; take care^\u00b0'.' themselves.\"\nHelhas Incorporated that; axiom -in i. the\nspiked plank *of i his anti-speed \"plat\nform, and\" to Impose that plank lon a\ndubious^constltuencyJ/Biggy; goes out\non'dark.-drearyjnlghts to toss his plank\nin '\\u25a0:. the 6 path of motor .car V travelers.\nBiggy is \\u25a0 determined that the j speed'or\ndinance 1 shallibe' inviolate though' every\ntire-.ihUhe'city :be torn .to, shreds.\nkEEjirbNjTHE '\\u25a0'HUJiT*:>'^^\n.1? Yesterday morning 'he was keen ;on\nthe \"r hunt for]\" speed maniacs.\" V. Accom\npanied jby\\j Policeman iFleld, \"i theMnde\nfatigable^chief*ofj:police;took\":up his\nvigil'? ln Slitter.* street near; Larkln, a\nplace fa vorediby.automobillsts .who use\ntha high 'sp^eed .clutch. Like a vigilant\ngeneral he: V ceremoniously.' stationed\nhimself 6n dne side; of the street. \"Gen-\"\nerousfy^ he J let Field i have the other!\nThe two men awaited their prey.\n:;tlll ;3^; 3^ o'clock v in^thet morning they\nwaited.\"; v'A\"* chief iof [police must not be\nfaiht^wheri^awaitingi* the ?of\nmisdemeanorites. F^/At 3 \"o'clock\" ln^ the\nmornlrigiithe^longjThours^ seemed Tabout\ntOshrlng5 theirireward:'>'Down;the;Sut- r\nter j street? hill fcarae;; a fear j driven .by.\nMartin iDunbar/of^the -;automo-'\nbile icompany,?ofv Golden i; Gate; avenueJ\nDunbar.- seemed Ito -be ibreakingi most ot\nthe speed laws i that Blggy,. had ever\nheard 3 tellj of.^,Thetindefatigable {chief\nof 1 police I, steppedllnto i the rroadway; and\nraised I the) majestic hand the \\u25a0 law\u2014\nhis;hand. 4 Somehow, lt'dld|not Impress\nDunbar.; -Field\": threw^a Aboard on the\nstreet* before &they S p ee dln g .jcajy^i Dun{\nbar,f Jerked '-Shis '^wheelti hard 'Caport;\ndodged I behind \\Bi ggy.Vdustlng his coat\ntails with ;the guards.'Jandi; sped\nup^the'streetltowardiyanlNess avenue. 1\nContinued an Page 12, Bottom Column 1\nPersian Shah Anns\nAgainst Assembly\nRuler Fails to Take Advice of\nParliament and Trouble\nIncreases\nSPECIAL DISPATCH TO THE CALL\n-.TEHERAN, June 17.\u2014 The situation\nis more serious today. The shah has\nnot answered the assembly's address,\nas he. promised yesterday to the cabi\nnet. .The assembly declares that his\nmajesty takes :no heed of Its advice\nand acts on his own accord. More ar\nrests are expected tonight.\n\"Several thousand armed \\u25a0 men have\nleft the provinces for Teheran and\nmore ..guns; and ammunition _- were\ntaken to the shah's camp today.\" 1\nwent to; visit his majesty's 'camp, but\nbeing without a permit was not alt\nlowed to 1 enter \"It. Judging from the\nexterior it Is well equipped.\nRUSSIAN FORCE WITHDRAWS\nTIFL.IS. June 17. Detachments of\nthe.o. Russian -.\"force under. General\nSnarski*; that recently.-- invaded Persian\nterritory in punishment for the depre\ndations* of Persian \"bandits are, now\nwithdrawing from the Persian frontier\nto Belessuever.' With the payment by\nPersia,,; of -the indemnity exacted by\nRussia^ the difficulty with Teheran is\nconsidered at an. end.-'\nThe presence ;of Russian troops on\nthe -Persian frontier had an irritating\neffect; on the i situation at Teheran and\nTabriz, v so-much so. that a dispatch re\nceived .hereV from Tabriz says /that\n1,500 members of various secret 'socie\nties volunteered ,to inaugurate an ex\npedition; to Teheran against' the shab.\nTURKISH I TROOPS CAD VAXCE\n,The .advance, of Turkish troops\nagainst' Urumlah,' In Persian\" Armenia,\nstill -continues. This, situation- arises\n\u2022fronvia\u00ab-boundary\u00bb dispute^and a ques\ntion: of sovereignty. The\" invaders have/\noccupiedr s anVimportant ;strateglc point\nneariSalmas,*;northtof Urumiah. Com\nmunication between c Tabriz and Uru\nmiah is] Interrupted.\"\nMRS. HARTJE GETS ALISIOXY\n.PITTSBURG,\" June 17\u2014 Mrs. Mary\nScott Hart J c,} wife (of Augustus I Hartr t Je,\nthe millionaire paper manufacturer\nwhose divorce V litigation\nagainst; his [wile hasibeen .widely pub\nlished,-,won another,, victory today, when\nby, a decision iof Judge 'Fraser \"she i was\nawarded ?5.000 \\u25a0 ajyear, alimony,^ $26.25(>\nforj court* expenses' and $7,000: for at\ntorney's {fees, rt Her/claims for expenses\narid 'counsel? fees '^were but slightly re\nduced'by, the court.'\nPAGES 11 TO 20\nPRICE FIVE CENTS.\n$10,000 FUND\nFOR OPTION IS\nQUICKLY ENDED\nFew Hundred Dollars Needed Is\nSubscribed and Papers\nAre Signed\nMayor Taylor and City Engineer\nManson Are Jubilant Over\nOutcome\ni\nAgreement Is Modified to Let\nQuestion Be Submitted\nto the Voters\nSan Francisco took the first step\nyesterday toward the actual acquisi\ntion of a municipal water supply.\nThe sum of $10,000 was paid to Elmer\nE. Smith and the city obtained there\nby full control of the valuable reser\nvoir sites in the Hetch Hetchy valley.\nFuture payments of $140,000 will give\nthe municipality complete possession\nof the lands.\nThe money for the initial install\nment was advanced by patriotic citi\nzens, who will be reimbursed when'ths\nelectors vote the necessary funds at a\nbond election. This \u2022lection. It Is un\nderstood, is to be held In the fall, when\nthe people of the city will be asked\nto vote bonds to acquire all the private\nholdings In the Hetch Hetchy and Lake\nEleanor districts, with the rights of\nway from the Sierras to San Francisco,\nincluding sites for dams, canals, and\nair other essentials to a well equipped\nwater system.\nAt the same time that the city took\nover the Smith holdings yesterday it\ncame into possession of the 160 acres\nbelonging to Mrs. Elizabeth CoveL\nThis eliminates the last of the private\nholdings from the Hetch Hetchy.\nOnly after Auditor Koster had re\nfused to pass the $10,000 appropriation\nof the supervisors were private sub\nscriptions solicited. In order that fu\nture payments may be protected from\nsuch*contingency a new provision was\nadded .to the agreement yesterday.\nwJiereby Smith consents to allow the\ncfty such extra time for the second in\nstallment as. may be consumed in plac\ning the matter before the people for\ntheir approval at the polls.\nFUND Qt'ICKLY COMPLBTBD\nOnly a few hundred dollars were\nneeded yesterday to complete the fund.\nThis waj quickly subscribed by John\nA. McGregor, president of the Union\nIron works; Supervisor George Center;\nJ. G. Harney, the contractor, and Ignatz\nSteinhart, manager of the Anglo-Call\nfornlan bank, who supplied a total of\n1380.\nThe details of the transaction were\narranged at the offices of the First na\ntional bank at 2 o'clock yesterday\nafternoon. The city was represented\nby Mayor Taylor, City Engineer Mars\nden Manson, Supervisor Giannini. chair\nman of the public utilities committee,\nand N. J. Manson of the city attorney's\noffice. Elmer Smith appeared with J. F.\nBurgln. the real estate dealer. John 11.\nSkinner, the assistant cashier of the\nFirst national bank, and Ignatz Stein\nhart were present as trustee* of the\nfund \"and James D. Phelan, who had\ncarried on the earlier negotiations, was\nalso in attendance.\nIt required but half an hour to eon\n'plete the. transaction. The stipula\ntions, including the new provision, were\n-signed by Smith and Mayor Taylor, the\nlatter acting for the city, and then two\nchecks were turned over to Smith and\nreceipts duly given. One Of the checks,\n\u2022for $2,923, was drawn on the Anglo- 1\nCalifornia bank, and the other, -for\n$7,077. on the First national bank.\n.Under the original agreement the\ncity was to make a second payment of\n$40,000 August 1 of this year, a third'\npayment to the amount of at least'\n$50,000 on or before August 1. 1910, the'\nremaining sum to bear Interest at the:\nrate of 6 per cent. This is modified by\nthe. following provision, which was\nagreed to yesterday:\nAGREEMENT IS MODIFIED\n\"It Is hereby further agreed by the\n-undersigned, Elmer E. Smith, that in\ncase the. payment. due August 1. 1903,\nunder the .above option shall be de\nlayed by adverse decision of any officer\nor officers of San Francisco having to\nact in the matter under the charter of\nsaid city this payment may be delayed\nuntil 90 days after.: the date of a pop\nular vote of the electors of the city and\ncounty of San Francisco authorizing or\nrefusing to authorize the acquisition of\nlands and source of municipal water\nsupply in the Sierra mountains, pro\nvided said vote be cast prior to Novem\nber 12, 1908.\"\nThis practically assures a prelimi\nnary, bond election on the Hetch Hetchy\nproject before November 12 of the pres\nent year.\nBy the terms of yesterday's purchase\nSan Francisco acquired 1.390 acres of\nland in and adjoining the Hetch Hetchy\nvalley In Tuolumne county. The sec\ntion,*; which i does not lie in the floor of\nthe Hejtch Hetchy. which Is to\" be used\nfor reservoir purposes, will be given to\nthe, United States government in ex\nchange for federal lands lying within\nthe. proposed' reservoir site.\nI\\u25a0\u00bbOfI \\u25a0\u00bb Of Smith's holdings which have,\npassed- into, the hands of the .city prac\ntically 560 acres lie In the Hetch Hetchy\nvalley or along the hillsides; 160 acres\narje in the TIltH valley. 322 in what Is\nknown as? the Hog ranch,' 160 acres in\"\"\nthe Canon 'ranch, and .163 acres in the\nMiddle Fork, homestead. Mayor Taylor,\nwas greatly pleased with* the results of\nyesterday's negotiations.\nFIRST STEPl TAKEN\n\"Whatever else we may get In the\nway r of. 1 a-, water he said, \"a\nSierra source Is an .absolute \"necessity.\nToday we took the first actual \"step\nContinued on Pa\u00abe 13, Middle Coluims t","height":"26316","width":"19371"}}
